<asn_lookup_guide>
<title>ASN AND BGP RECONNAISSANCE</title>

<critical>ASN (Autonomous System Number) analysis reveals an organization's complete IP infrastructure, peering relationships, and network topology. Large organizations operate their own ASNs; others use hosting providers whose ASNs indicate shared infrastructure. BGP data exposes IP ranges, geographic presence, upstream providers, and network architecture invisible to application-layer scanning.</critical>

<scope>
- ASN ownership and allocation research
- IP prefix enumeration per ASN
- BGP peering relationship analysis
- Network topology mapping
- Cloud provider ASN identification
- Geographic presence determination
- Upstream and downstream provider analysis
- IP range to organization correlation
- Historical BGP announcement tracking
- Network infrastructure fingerprinting
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify target organization's ASN(s).
2. Enumerate all IP prefixes announced by each ASN.
3. Map geographic distribution of announced prefixes.
4. Identify upstream providers and peering relationships.
5. Correlate ASN with cloud provider usage.
6. Analyze historical BGP data for infrastructure changes.
7. Cross-reference with reverse DNS and WHOIS.
8. Identify related ASNs through organizational links.
9. Map complete network topology and attack surface.
10. Document IP ranges for subsequent scanning.
</methodology>

<testing_techniques>
<asn_discovery>
{% raw %}
# ASN Discovery Methods

# 1. From known IP address
# Cymru WHOIS
whois -h whois.cymru.com " -v 93.184.216.34"
# AS | IP | BGP Prefix | Country | Registry | Allocated | AS Name
# 15133 | 93.184.216.34 | 93.184.216.0/24 | US | arin | 2008-06-02 | EDGECAST

# BGPView API
curl -s "https://api.bgpview.io/ip/93.184.216.34" | jq '.data.prefixes[].asn'

# 2. From domain name
# Get IP, then ASN
IP=$(dig +short A example.com | head -1)
whois -h whois.cymru.com " -v $IP"

# 3. From organization name
# PeeringDB search
curl -s "https://www.peeringdb.com/api/net?name__contains=Microsoft" | jq

# 4. Direct ASN search
# ARIN (Americas)
whois -h whois.arin.net "o Company Name"

# RIPE (Europe)
whois -h whois.ripe.net -T aut-num "Company Name"

# APNIC (Asia-Pacific)
whois -h whois.apnic.net "Company Name"

# 5. ASN Range lookup
# Major tech companies often have multiple ASNs
# Google: AS15169, AS396982, etc.
# Microsoft: AS8075, AS3598, etc.
# Amazon: AS16509, AS14618, etc.
{% endraw %}
</asn_discovery>

<prefix_enumeration>
{% raw %}
# IP Prefix Enumeration per ASN

# RADB (Routing Arbiter Database)
whois -h whois.radb.net -- '-i origin AS15169'
# Returns all prefixes announced by Google's main ASN

# BGPView API
curl -s "https://api.bgpview.io/asn/15169/prefixes" | jq '.data.ipv4_prefixes[].prefix'

# RIPE RIS
curl -s "https://stat.ripe.net/data/announced-prefixes/data.json?resource=AS15169" | jq

# Hurricane Electric BGP Toolkit
# https://bgp.he.net/AS15169#_prefixes

# Combine IPv4 and IPv6
curl -s "https://api.bgpview.io/asn/15169/prefixes" | jq -r '
  (.data.ipv4_prefixes[].prefix),
  (.data.ipv6_prefixes[].prefix)
'

# Aggregate overlapping prefixes
# Use aggregate6 or similar tools
curl -s "https://api.bgpview.io/asn/15169/prefixes" | \
    jq -r '.data.ipv4_prefixes[].prefix' | \
    aggregate6

# Output example for large ASN:
# 8.8.4.0/24
# 8.8.8.0/24
# 8.34.208.0/20
# ...hundreds of prefixes
{% endraw %}
</prefix_enumeration>

<peering_analysis>
{% raw %}
# BGP Peering and Upstream Analysis

# Get peers and upstreams
curl -s "https://api.bgpview.io/asn/15169/peers" | jq

# RIPE RIS peers data
curl -s "https://stat.ripe.net/data/asn-neighbours/data.json?resource=AS15169" | jq

# PeeringDB (peering policy and locations)
curl -s "https://www.peeringdb.com/api/net?asn=15169" | jq

# Upstream vs Peer vs Downstream
# Upstreams: Providers (transit)
# Peers: Direct connections (settlement-free)
# Downstreams: Customers

# BGPView relationships
curl -s "https://api.bgpview.io/asn/15169/upstreams" | jq
curl -s "https://api.bgpview.io/asn/15169/downstreams" | jq

# AS Path analysis
# Trace how routes propagate
# Identifies transit providers

# Hurricane Electric BGP
# https://bgp.he.net/AS15169#_graph
# Visual AS relationship graph

# Key indicators:
# Single upstream = Single point of failure
# Many peers = Well-connected organization
# Tier-1 upstreams = Global reach
{% endraw %}
</peering_analysis>

